# Skill Distiller (Cursor)

## Overview

Detection and authoring are different jobs. This rule owns detection
and the MDC formatting; the *authoring methodology* (description
optimisation, evaluation, iterative drafting) is borrowed from
Anthropic's [`skill-creator`](https://github.com/anthropics/skills/tree/main/skills/skill-creator)
(Apache 2.0).

We don't vendor skill-creator's scripts here because Cursor uses MDC
rules instead of `SKILL.md` files; its `package_skill.py` /
`improve_description.py` are SKILL.md-oriented and don't apply
directly. We borrow the *approach*:

1. Draft a description starting with "Use when..."
2. Generate 5-10 test prompts that should and shouldn't trigger the
   skill
3. Iterate the description until trigger accuracy is clearly correct
4. Document the rule body in the standard five-section shape

## When to Use

- A multi-step instruction has appeared in three separate sessions
- User asks "can you remember how I like to do X?"

## Steps

1. Confirm three repeats.
2. Pick a slug. Target path: `.cursor/rules/skills/<slug>.mdc`.
3. Draft the rule with `alwaysApply: false` and a `description` that
   starts with "Use when...". The description IS the trigger.
4. Generate trigger and non-trigger test prompts. Ask the user to
   review them. Iterate the description until match behaviour is right.
5. Write the body: Overview / When to Use / Steps / Pitfalls / Checklist.
6. Show the draft to the user before committing.
7. Prune now-redundant feedback memories from both
   `.cursor/memory/MEMORY.md` and `.cursor/rules/10-memory-index.mdc`.

## Pitfalls

1. Distilling on the second occurrence.
2. `alwaysApply: true` on skills. Reserve always-applied for
   protocol/persona/memory-index only.
3. Descriptions that don't start with "Use when...". Cursor matches
   on the first sentence of the description.
4. Skipping the trigger-prompt iteration. The whole reason
   skill-creator exists upstream is that description tuning matters.

## Checklist

- [ ] Three or more repeats confirmed
- [ ] `description` starts with "Use when"
- [ ] `alwaysApply: false`
- [ ] Trigger and non-trigger test prompts were reviewed
- [ ] Draft approved by user
- [ ] Superseded memories pruned from both MEMORY.md and the index rule
